segments.text: Okay.
First of all, to go to A&M, and second, to meet Gabe Anderson, who was really one of the finest human beings you'll ever meet, and was really quite an influence on me at A&M.
In what way?
Just being a good friend and a good roommate and being right, correct.
What do you mean correct?
Honest?
Well, honest.
He just had good human...
coordination with others, and just a fine man.
And he'd been a very successful man in business, I might add.
What happened to him?
What business?
Where'd he go?
He wanted to, and I might say I was very fortunate to get into C Battery, too, which maybe we can develop later.
Gabe Anderson went in on active duty, of course, same time the rest of us did.
He wound up in the 1st Army Division in Africa and then later in Europe and went through the war with that division.
And I understand was a very fine officer.
And when he came back, he really wanted to stay in the Army.
But then it developed that he did stay for, I guess, a couple of years, as I recall.
But then he decided to get out, and he went back home to Farwell.
Farwell, you know, is right in that great High Plains farm country over there.
And he went into the grain elevator business.
When he was in high school, he had worked for a grain elevator at Farwell.
And he knew something about it, and he liked it.
And that was good grain country.
This is before the, as I recall it, this is before the irrigation days, however, that he went into the grain elevator business then on his own.
I think he had a partner or two initially.
And then they just started irrigating that country and took off.
And dang, he had more grain elevators standing than most ranchers had cattle.
and just handled it beautifully.
And I think when you get into something that big, you've got to know what you're doing to do it well.
Anyway, he's been very, very successful.
We still, all through the years, we've corresponded.
Everybody's a poor letter writer now, but every once in a while, maybe the average of every six months, I'll call him and he'll call me.
And we'll literally talk for a half hour, 45 minutes over the telephone.
Well, I'm certain he's a multi-millionaire, but I don't have any idea.
But you'd never know it from his conduct or by comparing him today with what he always had been.
Okay.
When you went to A&M, when you first thought about going to A&M, did the idea of the military have anything to do with your decision?
Because it's a military school.
Everybody had to be in the Corps then.
No, it really didn't.
As a matter of fact, I knew it was a military school.
That didn't bother me, but I had no particular objectives in the military end of it.
I did think that, as I still do, that in this country and under our system, it's a good idea to be a reserve officer if you're capable and have the opportunities.
And if you're ever called in the Army, I think as a enlisted man, or in the services, or an officer, you should serve to the limits of your capacity.

I've had very promising citizen soldiers in World War II, for example, in some cases in Vietnam, who appeared to have everything on the ball you need, but when you suggested they be commissioned, they don't want it because they don't want the responsibility.
Well, of course, then that separates them.
I think there's an obligation to serve to your capacity.
But no, I had no, I had very little military knowledge and background at that stage.
And I knew that in the Spanish-American War, my father had just completed organizing a company, local company, to go to the Spanish-American War when, you know, it was a very brief war.
It was called off.
Sure.
He was too old to be...
to serve in World War I.
His father and his father's brother were in Hood's Coward Civil War.
And of course we didn't do a very good job of preserving the details on that, but that was a matter of proud history.
On my mother's side, her
Her father was too young for the Civil War, but his brothers were in the war.
And, of course, they had a better family history to hand down on that than the Becker side.
Those things fascinated me, but they didn't really set any goals for me in the military.
So I just went in to be an A&M cadet, or a student, and thereby a cadet, and that's where I started.
And at no time did you ever think of going to the military academy, for example.
No, not really.
Because one of your brothers went to Princeton, right?
Isn't that what you told me?
Yeah.
Oh, yeah, okay.
And so he left Texas, and I was wondering if your dad ever thought that you should leave Texas for any other university.
No, I never really had any desire to leave Texas.
In fact, I never got out of the state boundaries until I went there and went to a football game in Arkansas.
No, I never considered the military.
I didn't want, you know, it was not consciously after a military career.
And I think if I had been urged to go to West Point, for example, I probably would have turned down because it was, not because what I knew about it, but because of what I didn't know about it.
You just didn't know anything about the military.
That's right.
Okay, all right.
Now, what were your first impressions when you arrived at A&M?
Well, my first impressions were that I was in a totally different world.
But except for the pressures of being a fish, I liked everything I saw.
What do you mean, a totally different world?
In what way?
Well, I had just never been in an environment with people organized like that, with this vast plant.
which even in those days appeared to us to be a vast physical plant.
And I was having my horizon open on what education is.
And that first week, it just seemed too much to take in.
I guess I'm saying that's a country boy's reaction to going to college.
I had never been on that campus before.
That's another question I wanted to ask.
Never been on that campus.
So this is the first time that you have.
Of course, when you went to the A&M in those days, and after that first two weeks or so, I was in a military outfit, that takes over your life.
Okay, what outfit were you in again?
I was in C Battery Field Artillery.
First Battalion of the Field Artillery Regiment.
And the reason I was there because I met Gabe Anderson.
Right, right.
And where'd you live?
I lived in Leggett Hall those first two years, and then the second two years we moved over to the new area.
What was then the new area?
Quad, they called it now.
Did you eat at Sabisa?
I ate at Sabisa Hall.
What did you think of the food?
I thought it was good.
I always thought the food at A&M was good.
What did you think of the accommodations?
It wasn't that important.
Those rooms were small, and that old legged hall wasn't very fancy, and you had to sweep awful hard to get the dirt off the floor.
But that wasn't all that important.
We had an entirely different view of facility requirements then, I'm sure, as compared to today.
What was important, now?
The important thing to me, and I think all of us there, was we'd just come out of a, well, we were not really fully out of that depression in 37.
Sure, absolutely.
And I just felt darn lucky that I got to arrive there with the prospect of completing an education there.
Now, that really was, boy, that's what was important to me.
I knew what work was.
I'd learned that here.
Our father kept us busy all the time.
If I can hark back to that a bit, he had these five boys.
Of course, Brian's a little young, but the four of us had chores to do morning and night.
Naturally, you would in a place this big.
And when you get out of school in the summertime, the first thing we did was cut oats and shock them.
and thrashing.
Then we'd bale hay for seemed to me like months.
It was actually weeks.
And we'd haul cordwood to that cotton gin.
That boiler was fired by wood, furnace.
He'd use about 300 cords of wood a year.
And so each of us have a team of mules or a team of horses in the wagon to just haul cord after cord to stack over there.
that were cut out of these woods here on the place.
And if it wasn't time to start ginning cotton by the time that was done, we'd go to the cotton patches, whole cotton or something of that sort.
So anyway, I knew what worked.
And as a matter of fact, I knew that I was going to have to work
summer and at school to be able to make it than I did.
I remember when Dad, when I left to go to A&M, Dad handed me a checkbook and says, take this with you and use it when you need it.
Just remember, don't have any money.
And so that's the way I used it.
That's the way I used it.
Were you employed on your A&M?
I worked at what they call the student labor program.
You were allowed to work for the college 12 hours a week at $0.25 an hour.
And I did my full 12 hours every week beginning, I believe, the second semester of my freshman year.
I just was too consumed that first semester.
And you did everything.
shovel horse manure off the streets to cutting brush to tending lawns, just whatever had to be done.
There was a student labor force that did a lot of the maintenance.
Now, some of the more fortunate guys, I thought, were those that did janitor's work.
They were hard to come by, those jobs that did the dormitories.
And even the cleaner job was to be a waiter in the mess hall.
But I worked until my senior year.
I thought, I'm maybe getting ahead of the story, but I thought I was going to be editor of the Longhorn, we called it then.
A yearbook.
I had been elected editor.
And I was best paying job in school.
But I was also appointed cadet colonel.
And in that year, the administration had made some regulations that said that any
student could accumulate only so many student activity points.
Have you been aware of this?
No.
And the maximum number were 10.
If you were a member of one of the recognized academic clubs that corresponded to your major, for example, I believe that was two points.
If you were an officer in it, it was five points.
And so you can see that after a while, you can accumulate 10 points.
I was very active in a number of activities down there.
But when I was appointed cadet colonel, that's 10 points.
Editor of the yearbooks, 10 points.
Each one of them is the maximum.
So I had to resign.
as editor of the yearbook.
It was my choice.
And it was a proper choice.
You would have rather been the colonel than the editor.

I felt that was, as badly as I needed the money and as much as I had worked for that other job, I'd say I'd worked on it for two years before the yearbook, I still felt being leader of that cadet corps was clearly the choice.
Why?
When all was said and done, I said that my main objective was to get a good education.
But actually, I was a part of that bunch of men.
And whether it's, as we were talking this morning, whether it's a university or an army unit, it's not the plant or the facilities or the weapons.
It's the people that count.
And so I wanted to, I thought I was very fortunate.
I couldn't figure out how in the world I was chosen in the first place.
And I still don't know.
But there was no question.
I wanted to be the cadet colonel.
I never contemplated being it, really.
Even though I was Sergeant Major the year before, I just couldn't see.
I mean, I guess I wasn't confident enough.
I wasn't counting on it happening, in other words.
Tell me how it came about.
Well, as I say, I'm not certain how they choose the cadet colonel.
The military department makes most of the determination, I'm sure, but of course the president of the university always, at least in those days, he could approve or disapprove.
But they looked for someone whose academic standing was very important.
Activities and extracurricular activities and positions in them was important.
Obviously, the military aptitudes and
standing academically in military subjects, was very important.
I had been chosen the year before as the Corps Sergeant Major.
In other words, I was the senior non-commissioned officer in the Corps under Cadet Colonel Woody Varner, whom you may know of, later became President and Chancellor of the University of Nebraska.
And I'm sure he had a lot to do with it.
That is, his recommendation was considered.
And anyway.
So you had a position of leadership.
Yes.
In the Corps, no question about that.
I never got to command the Corps in the Army, but I did command the Corps at A&M.
And as far as you were concerned,
It was much more important to have this position dealing with people than have one making money.
Yes, and I took care of the money thing.
I could take you here down to camp and meet the president of the First National Bank, and he must be 75.
He was, of course, a young man then.
He's probably in his early 70s.
But anyway, he staked me.
I borrowed money from that bank, and I did each year a little bit, but he had to carry me that last year.
Dad always helped, but I figured I had to do at least half of it.
I was working two summers.
I worked what was then a good job.
Doing what?
$100 a month.
I had a crew.
of me and one other fella going all over this county for the Agricultural Stabilization Office measuring croplands.
You know, in those days they had controls on how much cotton.
Sure.
So forth.
And we measured it by chains in those days.
This is like the summer of 38 and 39?
Yeah.
And I got to mow, I got all over this county, and I got to mow people.
Farmers living on the farm, landowners living in town.
And that was a very fun experience, I might add.
No kidding.
And $100 a month.
That was big pay.
How'd you get that job?
I think the director of that program was a good Aggie.
I think that probably.
But my dad probably helped.
I was going to add a moment ago.
On this selection of the cadet colonel, I should have mentioned, because it's very important.
You know, at the end of your junior year, you go off to ROTC camp.
And that's really where the final tests are, whether they're consciously tested or not.
That's where the final test is.
Because then you get an opportunity for practical leadership of your peers as you're organized for various phases of that camp work.
And you get the opportunity.
demonstrate that you have learned what they've been teaching in the military science courses.
Well, did you go or did you not?
Oh, yes.
See, I went to my senior year before being, I mean my junior year before being selected for, appointed cadet colonel my senior year.
But when I got out of A&M, I owed something less than a thousand dollars.
And that looked like a mountain of debt to me.
My pay as a new second lieutenant on active duty was $125 a month.
And I paid that back on a lieutenant's pay the first two years I was out.
In those days, it cost about $500 to go to A&M
Direct cost.
For living, all expenses.
Were the farmers resentful in this area toward the controls and the Roosevelt administration?
They were.
And that may have influenced my opinion a moment ago, that I think farmers would just like to be free of all this.
They'd be willing to be free of subsidies if they could be free of controls.
and regulations, and some of these controls were indirect, I guess.
Oh, I had one farmer.
We had some interesting experience.
Some of them were very resentful of it, in fact, angry about it.
Most of them accepted it.
And most of the people, even though I might be in the far corner of the county, they probably knew my dad, so that kind of helped, you know.
But I remember right in this community, one farmer sent me word not to show up to measure his land.
And if I did, he'd be waiting with a shotgun.
Really?
Did you go do it?
I had to.
And he just bluffed.
We had no problem.
But he scared the hell out of me.
I bet you.
That's how extreme it was.
Some of them were that extremely bitter about it.
Tell me about hazing at A&M.
Hazing at A&M was accepted, basically, when I entered A&M.
My observation of it over four years was that hazing left something to be desired.
The outfit I was in, I never saw it.
I mean, you know, it hurts to be paddled with a board the way they did, but I never saw it done as just pure retribution.
And I never saw it done in anger.
And the only time I ever saw it overdone
in my opinion, in my outfit, was that the, what we call the, I think what we used to call it was pinning on the stripes.
A&M, after the first few weeks, they'd publish a list of appointments.
The leaders were appointed early.
the cadet commanders and first sergeants.
And then they fleshed that out after we all got down there.
I guess one reason was because they weren't sure who was going to show up.
So then each outfit, at least mine did, had a formation which if I, as a sophomore, got promoted to corporal, I got two stripes.
So each upperclassman had the privilege of pinning those stripes on.
That was two licks for the board.
Some of them, realizing how many licks you're going to get, were very, very soft with them.
But others who had a special relationship with you one way or another would let you have it.
But I say that was overdone simply because of the numbers involved, not still those elements that I mentioned that would make it really insupportable.
It just didn't exist.
I probably shouldn't comment beyond that, because I had never witnessed the hazing in other outfits.
But I think the board was misused in some outfits.
Now, this was a function, again, of leadership.
And we had commanders in that battery that I was in that just saw that it was never abused.
The controls on the sophomores, because they were freshly removed from being freshmen, were almost as strict as they were on the freshmen because they didn't want them to abuse hazing.
Now, I've just spoken of the physical hazing, or the board hazing.
There were other aspects of physical hazing, and there was some mental hazing, but the mental hazing I never thought really was objectionable.
It was just part of the
program.
Now, I might comment that having gone back to A&M in 1946 for three years on the staff, I think the mental hazing and probably the physical hazing were even worse, although the board was less used.
Did you think that hazing was a good idea or a bad idea?
If I were inventing it, I would not have put it in there.
But this built up over a number of years of tradition, and I'm sure I've seen it because I was there as a student and later as a member of the military staff.
It's had its phases and it's had its... What was the purpose, as far as you were concerned as a student?
First of all, the purpose of hazing, as I would assess it, and would still be, is to subordinate the...
the private.
You've got to do that somehow.
And you're not in ranks that often or that long.
You're in all ranks often.
But you don't have enough time to train as a military unit to accomplish this, devoting all day in uniform and formations.
So that's the first purpose.
Somehow, at the time I went to A&M,
They made you very much aware at the time you got there that there were no boys at A&M.
I don't know whether you heard that expression or not.
Anybody enrolled in that cadet corps is a man.
And so, in some way, this was designed to make a man, I guess.
Quickly.
Yeah.
And prove to those newcomers that they could be men.
not just at A&M, but at A&M, too, you'd hear the expression, or somehow that you can take it aspect was attached to Hazen.
And I really don't know.
In some organizations, I think it was a matter of punishment, too, but I don't think that that was the primary.
I think that had come fourth in this line of four.
As I knew it.
I think it may have shifted some emphasis, but of course, when I was back on the staff, I wasn't really that close to it.
You couldn't get, as a staff member, you don't get that close to it.
What did you like about the Corps?
Well, the main thing I liked about the Corps is that I felt a part of something defined.
I had a defined part in it.
I think I was conscious of the fact that I didn't know where all those boys came from, but I knew I came, I'm a country boy.
But that sort of equalized us at Cadet Corps, because we were all there on the same basis.
We all dressed alike.
We all did the same thing except in our classrooms and when we went home.
So it didn't make any difference if you were wealthy or poor?
It didn't matter whether you were wealthy or poor.
It didn't matter whether you were a member of the Houston Country Club or had your recreation, hunting and fishing, as I did largely.
It just was a great equalizer.
And of course, that meant that we all had the same responsibility and same opportunity at each level.
And of course, I never really thought of these terms, but I probably wouldn't have been a cadet colonel if it weren't that way.
I mean, you know, if there were any gradations of
who you are because of where you came from.
It was a great thing, and a great spirit there.
That was another thing you liked?
Oh, tremendous, you bet.
I liked the spirit.
That old Aggie spirit, it doesn't take long for you to get it, and it becomes more and more ingrained, and the old all for one, one for all means something.
I have been, of course, in my military career over much of the world.
Well, certainly not all of it, but only one place was I ever stationed in my thirty years of service where I didn't have at least one other Aggie to have a muster with on April 21st.
No kidding.
Where was that?
And we always had them.
That was in Yugoslavia.
I was .
And there weren't too many Aggies there.
No.
But if I can digress a minute, Fran, of course, was very my wife.
And by the way, we haven't gotten into our kids and things yet.
But I'd like to talk about them some when the opportunity's proper.
But Fran, you know, was brought up down there.
Her dad was a graduate of A&M on staff down there.
He was in the experiment station.
But anyway, we both felt very oriented toward A&M.
And on that occasion in Yugoslavia, she and I were consciously observing the occasion.
And seated in our home there in Belgrade, and the phone rang.

And it was Colonel Chester Schaefer of the class of 33, Army, and Major George, Lieutenant Colonel I guess he was at that time, George Cooper, class of 42, that I'd gone through the war with and was a great friend.
And Chester Schaefer and I for years, we didn't write, but we'd call each other.
And somehow we got into the contest of
When I'd place the call, I'd try to hook him into accepting a collect call and vice versa.
But we had a long conversation.
We'd succeeded in that case.
I didn't feel that if I'd accepted this guy's call from Schaefer and found out he was there, I felt defeated.
But we had a long conversation from Frankfurt, Germany to Belgrade.
after we'd said about all there was to be said, I started sort of signing off, and Chester said, well, now, Becker, don't hang up on me.
He said, you're paying for this call, don't you know?
And I said, Chester, don't you know that nobody can reverse charges into Yugoslavia?
Which they couldn't do.
So he had to pay for that call, after all.
He thought I was paying for it.
But...
That A&M spirit stays with you forever?
It does.
I don't know.
I've never found... Well, the West Point Society meets wherever they are, their people, each year.
Never anything like this A&M must have.
They don't have the spirit that A&M does.
Well, they don't have the ceremony to it.
What about just the spirit?
Do they have the spirit?
I don't think so.
I don't think it's the same.
I think they have a fine spirit at West Point, but I don't think, this may be precious, but I don't think it matches the A&M's.
I don't know what the A&M student body's status of spirit is now, frankly.
I don't really know.
Were there, of course, those are some of the things that you liked about the Corps.
Were there some things that you disliked about the Corps when you were there?
Anything?
I can't think of a thing that I disliked about the Cadet Corps.
Nothing.
At any year.
Now, don't get me wrong.
There were times when I just didn't like it worth a bit that we fish were called out to drill an extra hour in the day.
I could recognize when we first got there we had to have training to be able to march properly.
But there were times when I thought it was excessive.
I mean, you know, things of that sort, but as far as the Corps and what it stood for and what it did and how it was organized and operated, I thought it was nothing but right.
And I, uh, we'll get into the downgrading of the Corps later, but at that time I think it was right.
Okay.
Now, you became a general.
In which way do you think that the Corps helped your advancement in the military?
Well, I think the Cadet Corps at A&M is a very serious, was a very serious military organization.
And to the extent of our capacity as young cadets, we didn't know we were copying the Army, but our mentors there had us aim just in the same direction.
So it was a little miniature Army organization.
After I left A&M, I came to learn that a lot of our yells that we'd do at football games really originated at West Point.
And I'm sure military instruction over the years brought them in there.
But the main thing that the Cadet Corps helps anybody who chooses a military career, and I don't think it's essential, obviously, because they're successful

officers who never went to an ROTC school but the main thing is that it gives you that succession of experiences that add up to cumulative leadership abilities for example in those days when you entered A&M as a freshman you were a private
In the field artillery training, in the marching formation, you were in the position of a private, corresponding to what it was in the Army.
When you were a sophomore, if you were measured up, you were a corporal and you were in charge of a few people.
During those times, you were either in military formation or in military instruction, practical instruction.
Junior, you were a sergeant, and that in large.
You became a platoon sergeant or section chief.

And then, of course, as an officer, if you were fortunate enough to be selected as a battery company and troop commander or a battalion commander or a regimental commander or the corps commander, you accumulated in that senior year a great deal of practical experiences in leading others, directing and leading others.
Discipline was good in the cadet corps at A&M when I was there.
Excellent, I would say.
But still, running an outfit wasn't automatic.
That company commander or that battalion commander or regimental commander and so forth, they had to lead.
And they did.
And they did their very best.
And most of them who were selected for those jobs did well.
because they were selected well.

So it's just a miniature range of experience that you then go into the Army and match as you go up, except with greater responsibilities and greater knowledge required and greater preparation required to do the military things.
Do you think that there was anything in the
Corps that in any way hindered your ability to become successful in the military?
Held you back?
I can't think of a thing.
Never considered a thing.
I think it was all plus.
I think being in the Corps hindered to some extent
the academic side, but not very seriously.
Because the nature of our young people is such that if they hadn't had those extra military things to do, they'd probably been goofing off anyway instead of studying.
And we had more directed study time as freshmen and sophomores than most free students were put to it anyway.
Now, you were a leader in the Corps, and then you became a leader in the military.
Did the fact that you were in the Corps have an impact on developing that role of leadership?
Well, I'm sure it did for the basic reason I state, and that is that I got experience in leadership there.
Right.
I don't think theand, of course, in those days, we were trained to
have knowledge in a particular branch of the Army, which you don't do anymore.
That was helpful too, very helpful.
As a matter of fact, when we were ordered to active duty, my first job was with a battery of artillery.
That's the proper level to start your experience.
And I'm not suggesting that we were superior at all to the West Point graduate, but the West Point graduate
that was in that outfit with me had had a non-branch material, a branch in material training with three months of service school.
And that three months just didn't catch him up to where A&M graduates were in their branch knowledge and capabilities.
So really,
We started out an advantage to those other counterparts that didn't have ROTC and full military training as in the military schools like A&M and BMI and so forth.
Were some of the professional soldiers at A&M at that time, were those professionals, did they have an impact on you?
Oh, yes.
I think the officers, of course, had a great deal more because we were more direct contact with the officers.
We had some fine non-coms there.
Were there any that you were particularly close to?
Well, I was close to Sergeant Thomas, I remember.
A few.
Now, I became Sergeant Thomas in
other sergeant, but I came close to both of them in the same way.
I was a member of the A&M pistol team, and at one time Thomas was our coach and this other sergeant, I can't call his name.
Later, Captain Inslow was our officer supervisor.
Incidentally, you've heard a lot about A&M's national football championship team, but we had the national championship in pistol.
Really?
When I was there.
No kidding.
Very, very fine pistol team.
competed with all the other ROTC schools that were willing to compete.
Anyway, that's how I became very close to those two particular sergeants.
Then, of course, in the course of the year, we'd get to know these non-con pretty well because we'd be training with them.
They'd be our instructors at the low level, you know, on the practical level.
We had some that had been there a long, long time.
They liked ANU.
by and large.
In those days, you know, if you enlisted for a position and did it well, you could stay there.
Right.
At the same rank.
In the 1930s.
That's right.
What do you think was the quality of officers that were graduated from A&M?
Let's talk about that.
Did you think that those young second lieutenants who were A&M grads were
top notch or mediocre or average?
Were they well trained?
I think that on the whole they were absolutely outstanding as a category of input to the officer corps.
By that I mean as a source.
And this was not just my judgment, but I say that for example in World War II.
I was in the 1st Cavalry Division, went through the whole war with it.
We had a number of A&M men in the division when we went overseas, a lot of A&M officers.
